docs.abstract: Two billionaire friends of President Trump say they cannot recall him ever doing his own grocery shopping, although he can handle a shopping cart.
docs.snippet: Two billionaire friends of President Trump say they cannot recall him ever doing his own grocery shopping, although he can handle a shopping cart.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Just when it seemed like Tuesday’s “Make America Great Again” rally in Florida would end with the typical punch list — Democrats, journalists, immigrants — President Trump added new spice to his usual extemporaneous potpourri by asserting that supermarket shoppers need to show valid identification in the checkout aisle.

headline.main: Trump Says You Need an ID to Buy Groceries. Shoppers Say, ‘Huh?’
headline.print_headline: Picking Up Groceries With Trump? Bring an ID

docs.abstract: In the third day of testimony in Paul Manafort’s tax and bank fraud trial, witnesses described how his finances deteriorated after losing his Ukrainian client.
docs.snippet: In the third day of testimony in Paul Manafort’s tax and bank fraud trial, witnesses described how his finances deteriorated after losing his Ukrainian client.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALEXANDRIA, Va. — A day after describing in detail how millions of dollars in payments from Ukrainian oligarchs enabled Paul Manafort to live in luxury through 2014, federal prosecutors outlined on Thursday how his financial fortunes reversed so sharply in subsequent years that he made his Manhattan condominium available on Airbnb.

headline.main: Prosecutors Document Paul Manafort’s Reversal of Fortune After 2014
headline.print_headline: Prosecutors Say Manafort Turned to Fraud as His Luxury Lifestyle Fell Apart

docs.abstract: The statement by Defense Secretary Jim Mattis was yet another sign that the diplomatic thaw between Washington and Pyongyang is coming to an end.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Defense Secretary Jim Mattis opened the door on Tuesday to restarting large-scale military exercises on the Korean Peninsula, appearing to contradict President Trump, who had labeled the war games costly and “provocative” two months ago in trying to lower tensions with North Korea.

headline.main: Pentagon May Restart Major War Games Amid Rising Tensions With North Korea
headline.print_headline: U.S. May Restart War Exercises With South Korea

docs.abstract: The president tried to make China the scapegoat for his administration’s stalled negotiations with Pyongyang. Beijing accused him of “magical logic.”
docs.snippet: The president tried to make China the scapegoat for his administration’s stalled negotiations with Pyongyang. Beijing accused him of “magical logic.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Wednesday tried to make China the scapegoat for his stalled diplomacy with North Korea, accusing it of undermining the American-led pressure campaign against Pyongyang because of an escalating trade dispute with the United States.

headline.main: Trump Accuses China of Undermining Diplomacy With North Korea
headline.print_headline: Trump Says China Meddles In Strategy on North Korea

docs.abstract: Joseph H. Hunt will lead the department’s civil division, which defends the administration in legal challenges over issues such as census questions and lawsuits against the president.
docs.snippet: Joseph H. Hunt will lead the department’s civil division, which defends the administration in legal challenges over issues such as census questions and lawsuits against the president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A bipartisan group of senators confirmed Joseph H. Hunt to lead the Justice Department’s civil division, one of the agency’s most senior roles, in a rare show of cooperation at a time when they have clashed over a host of other presidential nominees.

headline.main: Trump Administration Picks Career Justice Dept. Official to Defend Its Policies
headline.print_headline: Justice Dept. Veteran Confirmed by Senate To Lead Civil Division

docs.abstract: In his decision not to attend summit meetings in Asia this fall, the president will miss an opportunity to calm frazzled relationships in the region. And China could step in, analysts said.
docs.snippet: In his decision not to attend summit meetings in Asia this fall, the president will miss an opportunity to calm frazzled relationships in the region. And China could step in, analysts said.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHARLOTTE, N.C. — As President Trump hardened his stance on trade with Canada, one of the nation’s closest allies, the White House said Friday that Mr. Trump would not be traveling to Asia for a round of economic and security meetings with allies this fall.

headline.main: Trump to Skip Meetings in Asia as He Keeps a Distance With Allies
headline.print_headline: President Plans to Skip Talks With Asian Allies This Fall, White House Says

docs.abstract: The vote of Senator Susan Collins, a Maine Republican who backs abortion rights, is critical to the confirmation of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, President Trump’s Supreme Court pick.
docs.snippet: The vote of Senator Susan Collins, a Maine Republican who backs abortion rights, is critical to the confirmation of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, President Trump’s Supreme Court pick.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s views on abortion took center stage in the Senate on Tuesday after he assured a key Republican senator that he believed the 1973 Roe v. Wade decision was “settled law” — a comment that Democrats and abortion rights advocates derided as a meaningless dodge.

headline.main: Roe Is ‘Settled Law,’ Kavanaugh Tells Collins. Democrats Aren’t Moved.
headline.print_headline: Court Nominee Called Roe v. Wade ‘Settled Law’

docs.abstract: Critics said the inclusion of Bruce Ohr on the list of those whose clearances were revoked or under review was an abuse of presidential power and an intrusion on the independence of law enforcement.
docs.snippet: Critics said the inclusion of Bruce Ohr on the list of those whose clearances were revoked or under review was an abuse of presidential power and an intrusion on the independence of law enforcement.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the White House announced on Wednesday that President Trump was revoking or reviewing the security clearances of former officials who have emerged as some of his chief political antagonists, the list also included a little-known career Justice Department official, Bruce Ohr.

headline.main: Little-Known Justice Dept. Official Makes Trump’s Security Clearance List
headline.print_headline: Unlikely Name Is Found Among Bitter Antagonists
